#X text 34 150 The actual 'synthesis' part \, regarding the oscillaotr \, is sometimes the less important piece \, or actually just a start point. Many other effect processing is widely used in synthesis and we'll see many of them in later chapters \, as well as other more complex techniques such as Granular Synthesis and more. Nonetheless \, we can jump ahead and include important day to day processes that we all know \, before we get into them in details. I'm talking about a reverb \, for intance \, used in this patch., f 64;
#X text 566 376 (amplifier);
#X text 683 399 filter;
#X text 612 463 reverb;
#X text 595 264 Oscillator (actual sound wave synthesis);
#X text 602 303 envelope (amplitude controller);
#X text 34 29 Now that we laid down the most basic bare minimum \, we'll expand it a bit and organize things. A synth has sound generator source which actually does synthesize a sound. The basic unit of this is the Oscillator. Then we have the contollers \, like pitch and gate (note on / note off) from MIDI input. All the rest is actually applying effects to the sound to shape it and the most essencial one is the amplifier \, used to shape the sound attack and release via something like an envelope., f 64;
#X text 653 507 There you go \, this is already somewhat decent and usable..., f 30;
#X text 767 327 Notice how the slow attack and release is an important, f 30;
#X obj 529 192 mono 100, f 17;
#X text 668 185 pitch / gate controller \, with pitch portamento (modulation) at 100 ms, f 36;
#X text 34 269 Let's keep breaking things down. We have a sawtooth oscillator here \, which has a rich partial content as shown in previous examples. We're applying another effects processor that we have already checked in details \, a filter (a resonant lowpass to be more precise) via the [moog~] object \, an object that mimics the behaviour or analog gear and has an overdrive parameter set via the 3rd argument., f 64;
#X text 34 378 In this chapter we'll see some basic synthesis techniques. This includes adding more effects (like Ring Modulation and Tremolo) \, presenting new ways to create complex sound sources (like with FM) \, but mostly other ways to modulate and shape the sound by controlling the parameters. For now \, in this simple patch \, we have a portamento \, which is a pitch modulation \, from note to note. Also \, the envelope is a controller that shapes the sound., f 64;
#X text 34 488 So we'll start now with other kinds of basic modulations \, which is quite important in sound synthesis. all of these are "slow" or "low frequency modulation" \, not to be confused with other kinds of modulations we'll see in the "Modulation.Synthesis" chapter \, becuase those are "high frequency modulation" and include Amplitude and Frequency modulation., f 64;
